record_data.record_plain_text: Section 4 - Receipt and Delivery of Gas 4.1 Transporter agrees to receive, transport and deliver scheduled volumes of Gas tendered by shipper at given receipt points on each Day, on a firm or interruptible basis as designated in the applicable transportation agreement, up to the maximum daily transportation quantity (or demand quantity) for each receipt point. It is the intent of Transporter and shipper that all volumes tendered by shipper at receipt points or received by shipper at delivery points shall, to the maximum extent possible, flow at uniform, constant rates. 4.2 Notwithstanding any other provision of this Operating Statement, Transporter's obligation to receive, transport and deliver Gas shall be subject to Transporter's own operating requirements, any applicable local, state or federal regulatory requirements, and the availability of capacity sufficient to provide service to all similarly-situated shippers in accordance with the priorities set forth in Section 6. In no event shall Transporter be obligated to deliver or receive a quantity of Gas during any given Day that differs from the scheduled quantity for such Day. If the actual quantity of Gas received during any Day for transportation services differs from the scheduled quantity, then Transporter shall be obligated to deliver that Day the lesser of the actual quantity received or the scheduled quantity. Transporter has the right not to accept any Gas at receipt points or deliver Gas at delivery points if volumes are less than 500 Mcf per Day at any receipt point or delivery point. 4.3 Shipper shall provide and Transporter shall retain, at no cost to Transporter, shipper's proportional share of Fuel.

Section 3 - Governmental Regulation and Actions 3.1 Any transportation agreement and services to be provided thereunder shall be subject to all valid existing and future state, local and federal laws, orders, rules, regulations, or proclamations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction or control over the parties thereto or the subject matter thereof including, but not limited to, the provisions of Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations implementing Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and the Louisiana Natural Resources and Energy Act of 1973, as amended, and the regulations promulgated thereunder. 3.2 Notwithstanding any of the other provisions of this Operating Statement, if at any time any federal or state governmental authority shall take any action which is, with respect to or as a result of the transportation services provided for under this Operating Statement or a transportation agreement, designed to subject or otherwise subjects either party or any of Transporter's pipeline or related facilities to any different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the date a transportation agreement is executed (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted by any such party) and such greater or different regulation or jurisdiction shall materially reduce the net benefits of such transportation agreement to either party, then upon written notice to the other, the party so affected may at any time thereafter or effective one (1) Day prior to the effective date of such action terminate such transportation agreement without further obligation to the other party, except in the case of shipper to make payment for services rendered thereunder and, in the case of either Transporter or shipper to correct any Gas imbalance existing on the date of such termination. 3.3 Transporter shall not be required to provide transportation services to shipper unless Transporter and shipper have obtained, as appropriate, all governmental authorizations for services to be provided by Transporter and shipper related to those transportation services to be rendered by Transporter, including services that are necessary for Gas to be delivered into and received from Transporter's facilities. 3.4 If any governmental or regulatory body exercising jurisdiction over the transportation services hereunder currently charges or later establishes fees for the filing of applications or reports in conjunction with a transportation agreement or the transportation services provided thereunder, shipper shall reimburse or cause to be reimbursed Transporter, upon billing, for any fees so paid by Transporter.

Section 5 - Character of Service 5.1 Firm Transportation Service. (a) Firm transportation of Gas is made available to shipper by Transporter when: (i) Transporter has determined that it has sufficient available and uncommitted capacity to perform the transportation services for shipper; and (ii) shipper and Transporter have executed a transportation agreement for the firm transportation of Gas. (b) Firm transportation service shall be subject to curtailment or interruption as provided in paragraph 11.2 or Section15. 5.2 Interruptible Transportation Service (a) Interruptible transportation of Gas is made available to shipper by Transporter when (i) Transporter has determined that it is operationally able to render such transportation services after considering all firm service obligations; and (ii) shipper and Transporter have executed a transportation agreement for the interruptible transportation of Gas. (b) Interruptible transportation service is subject, at any time and from time-to-time, to partial or total interruption or cessation at Transporter's sole and unfettered discretion for any reason, upon Transporter providing oral or written notice prior to (when possible) or contemporaneously with such interruption or cessation. Transporter has absolutely no liability whatsoever in damages or otherwise for any such interruption or cessation. 5.3 Authorized Overrun Service (a) Upon request from shipper at the time it nominates firm or interruptible service, Transporter may, in its sole discretion, approve and schedule for receipt or delivery a quantity of Gas greater than shipper's maximum daily transportation quantity (or demand quantity) and shipper's Fuel quantity specified in the transportation agreement. Authorized overrun service will be available only if (i) Transporter determines in its sole discretion that it has sufficient capacity after first scheduling all firm and interruptible transportation services within the limits of all shippers' maximum daily transportation quantities (or demand quantities), and (ii) shipper has a designated authorized overrun service rate in its firm or interruptible transportation agreement. Authorized overrun service will be scheduled on a first-come, first-served basis, with the priorities established in Section 6. (b) Authorized overrun service is interruptible and is subject, at any time and from time to time, to partial or total interruption or cessation at Transporter's sole and unfettered discretion for any reason, upon Transporter providing, when possible, either oral or written notice prior to or contemporaneously with such interruption or cessation. Transporter has absolutely no liability whatsoever in damages or otherwise for any such interruption or cessation.

Section 20 - Miscellaneous 20.1 Odorization: Transporter will notify shipper in the event odorization of shipper's Gas transported under a transportation agreement is required by any statute, ordinance, rule or regulation. It is specifically understood and agreed that shipper is responsible for any and all odorization that is or may be required by any statute, ordinance, rule or regulation, and that shipper shall construct, maintain and operate any facilities required for the performance of this obligation. Shipper agrees that Transporter shall not be obliged to odorize the Gas received, transported and delivered by Transporter under a transportation agreement, and that shipper's indemnity obligation in favor of Transporter set forth in Section 13 shall include a duty to indemnify and defend Transporter for any and all claims, losses, damages, costs and expenses (including attorneys fees) arising out of liability predicated upon failure to odorize or inadequate odorization of any Gas received, transported and delivered hereunder. 20.2 Abandonment: Without admitting to or acquiescing in the jurisdiction of the Louisiana Office of Conservation over this Operating Statement or transportation agreement pursuant to the provisions of LSA R.S. 30:555(b) or of any body, either State or Federal and reserving all rights with respect thereto, Transporter and shipper contract and agree that each party will support any application of the other seeking approval of the abandonment of service under a transportation agreement when such transportation agreement is terminated pursuant to its terms. Shipper and Transporter confirm to each other that the cessation of service at the termination of a transportation agreement is an important consideration to each, and to this end, both contract and agree that neither will take any action that may be construed by any regulatory official or body that has jurisdiction as a basis for requiring deliveries of Gas by Transporter to shipper after the lawful termination of said transportation agreement. The parties agree that at all times they will take appropriate action, and cooperate with the other, to the end that delivery of Gas hereunder may be abandoned at the lawful termination of the transportation agreement and both agree that the lawful termination of the transportation agreement, for whatever reason, shall constitute authority and consent to abandon service therein.

Section 7 - Rates, Fees, Billing, Payment and Reporting 7.1 A firm shipper shall pay Transporter each Month, as determined by the transportation agreement, either (a) the Monthly reservation fee multiplied by shipper's maximum daily transportation quantity (or demand quantity) specified in the transportation agreement, or (b) the daily reservation fee multiplied by shipper's maximum daily transportation quantity (or demand quantity) specified in the transportation agreement multiplied by the number of Days in the Month of flow. Additionally, shipper shall pay a commodity fee for each MMBtu of Gas delivered to Transporter during the Month of flow. 7.2 An interruptible shipper and a shipper utilizing the authorized overrun service shall pay Transporter a transportation fee for each MMBtu of Gas delivered to Transporter during the Month of flow. 7.3 A firm or interruptible shipper authorized by Transporter to utilize the authorized overrun service shall pay Transporter a transportation fee for each MMBtu of Gas delivered to Transporter during the Month of flow. 7.4 Transporter may at any time and from time to time agree to adjust the fee at one or more points under a transportation agreement between Transporter and shipper to a discounted fee for a specified term. Such discounted fee(s) shall be communicated and agreed to as an amendment to the transportation agreement. 7.5 Shipper shall pay Transporter all fees required by the FERC, the Louisiana Office of Conservation and any other regulatory or governmental body related to the services provided by Transporter under the transportation agreements, including but not limited to filing, reporting, and application fees. Transporter shall not include the amount so collected in establishing general system rates. 7.6 On or before the twentieth (20th) Day of each Month Transporter shall render to shipper a statement for the preceding Month showing the total quantities of Gas received under the transportation agreement at the receipt points, the quantity of Gas retained by Transporter, the quantity redelivered to Shipper at the delivery points, the fees due under the transportation agreement and other information sufficient to explain and support any adjustments made by Transporter in determining the amount billed. On or before the last Day of each Month, shipper shall make payment for all amounts set forth on the statement referred to above. If the invoiced amount is not paid when due, interest on any unpaid portion shall accrue at an interest rate equal to two percent (2%) plus the prime rate as quoted by The Wall Street Journal or at the highest rate permitted by applicable law, whichever is lower, from due date until date paid. If default continues after ten (10) Days' written notice from Transporter to shipper, Transporter may suspend receipt and delivery of Gas under the transportation agreement without prejudice to any other available remedies at law or in equity. If collection efforts are required, shipper agrees to pay all legal expenses and court costs (including attorney fees and expert testimony) required in these collection efforts. 7.7 If any overcharge or undercharge in any form whatsoever shall at any time be found and the bill therefore has been paid, Transporter shall refund any amount of overcharge or shipper shall pay any amount of undercharge, as the case may be, within thirty (30) Days after final determination thereof, provided that no retroactive adjustment will be made beyond a period of twenty-four (24) Months from the date of the invoice sought to be corrected. 7.8 Transporter and shipper shall have the right at any and all reasonable times to examine the books and records of the other party to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement or charge, computation or demand, made pursuant to the transportation agreement.

Section 15 - Force Majeure 15.1 The term "Force Majeure" as employed herein means acts of God; strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances; acts of the public enemy; wars; blockades; insurrections; riots; epidemics; landslides; lightning; earthquakes; fires; storms; hurricane or threat thereof; floods; washouts; or other natural disasters; threat of physical harm or damage resulting in the evacuation or shutdown of facilities necessary for the production, delivery, receipt or storage of Gas; arrests and restraints of the government, either federal or state, civil or military; civil disturbance; explosions, breakage, breakdown or accident to machinery, equipment or lines of pipe; the necessity or desirability of repairing, altering, maintaining, inspecting, replacing, changing the size of, substituting or removing machinery, equipment, pipelines or appurtenant facilities; failure of equipment or materials; an unscheduled shutdown of plants or facilities, or the partial or entire suspension of the operation of plants or facilities caused by an event of the character herein defined as constituting Force Majeure; the failure or inability of Transporter to provide transportation service due to an event of Force Majeure or to the curtailment of firm transportation; and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise (but not including economic hardship), not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension, and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable, wholly or in part, to prevent or overcome. "Force Majeure" includes (i) in those instances where either party hereto is required to obtain or maintain servitudes, right-of-way grants, permits, exceptions or licenses to enable such party to fulfill its obligation under any transportation agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or maintain, or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, right-of-way grants, permits, exceptions or licenses, and (ii) in those instances where either party hereto is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency (federal, state or municipal, civil or military) to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under any transportation agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or maintain, or the delays of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such material and supplies, permits and permissions. It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the party having the difficulty and that the above requirement that any Force Majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the party having the difficulty. 15.2 If either party hereto is unable, wholly or in part, by Force Majeure, to carry out its obligations under any transportation agreement, other than the obligation to make payments of amounts due hereunder, then upon such party giving notice and reasonably full particulars of such Force Majeure in writing to the other party within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the obligations of the party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such Force Majeure or other causes herein specified, shall be suspended during the continuance of such cause, but for no longer period, and such cause shall be remedied so far as possible with all reasonable dispatch.

Section 14 - Limitation of Liability In no event shall Transporter be liable to shipper for any special, direct, incidental, or consequential damages of any character, including without limitation, loss of use, loss of revenue, cost of capital, cancellation of permits, unabsorbed transportation or storage charges, termination of contracts, tort or contract claims other than contract claims arising out of an agreement between Transporter and shipper, loss of production or any other form of consequential damage suffered by shipper, and irrespective of whether claims of such damages are based upon contract, warranty, negligence, strict liability or otherwise, including damages attributable to Transporter's sole or concurrent negligence.

Section 19 - Assignment If shipper desires to assign or transfer its rights under its transportation agreement, shipper shall request, in writing, Transporter's consent for such assignment. Any assignment by shipper to an assignee that meets or exceeds credit worthiness standards of Transporter, to be determined within Transporter's sole discretion, will be permitted; however, if the assignee does not meet or exceed the creditworthiness standards of Transporter, such assignment will not be permitted. Subject to Transporter's consent to any assignment, the transportation agreement shall bind and inure to the benefit of the successors and assigns of Transporter and shipper. If shipper makes an assignment in violation of the above requirements, then the Transporter may immediately terminate the transportation agreement. Transporter has the right to assign this Operating Statement and any transportation agreement.

Section 18 - Nominations and Scheduling (a) Nominations for Gas are to be submitted to the attention of the Gas Scheduling Department in writing, by fax or other electronic means designated by Transporter. (b) By 11:30 a.m. Central Clock Time on the business Day before Gas is desired to flow, shipper shall submit to Transporter a nomination which includes the following: (i) shipper's name, contact name and phone number; (ii) transportation agreement number assigned by Transporter; (iii) daily quantity of Gas to be received by Transporter at each receipt point, before deducting any quantity for Fuel due Transporter; (iv) daily quantity of Gas to be delivered by Transporter at each delivery point, before deducting any quantity for Fuel due Transporter; (v) begin date for the nomination and end date for the nomination (not to extend past the last Day of the Month in which Gas would first flow under the nomination); and (vi) shipper's contract numbers with upstream and downstream parties from which and to which Gas will be received and delivered. Transporter may, at its sole discretion, accept nominations at such later time as operating conditions permit, and may waive any nomination requirement. A quantity nominated for receipt less Fuel and a quantity nominated for delivery are to be equal, unless shipper is making up an imbalance with the prior approval of Transporter. A quantity nominated as an authorized overrun is to be separately stated on the nomination. (c) The quantity of Gas nominated by shipper will be deemed the confirmed scheduled quantity by Transporter at 4:00 p.m. Central Clock Time each Day, unless Transporter provides notice to Shipper of a different scheduled quantity prior to 4:00 p.m. Central Clock Time. J-W Pipeline Company Operating Statement Section: 20-Section 18 (Nominations and Scheduling) Issued: November 21, 2013 Version: (1.0.0) Effective: December 1, 2013

Section 17 - Applicable Law THIS OPERATING STATEMENT AND ANY AGREEMENT SHALL BE INTERPRETED, CONSTRUED AND GOVERNED BY THE LAWS OF THE STATE OF TEXAS, EXCLUDING ANY CONFLICTS OF LAW RULE THAT WOULD APPLY THE LAW OF ANOTHER JURISDICTION.

Section 10 - Metering Fee If the aggregate quantity of Gas tendered by shipper or accepted by Transporter under a transportation agreement during any Month at any given receipt point or delivery point equals a quantity less than the product of (i) three hundred (300) MMBtu per Day and (ii) the number of Days in the Month during which shipper tendered Gas to Transporter in accordance with a confirmed nomination, then Transporter may, at its election, charge shipper a metering fee of three hundred and fifty dollars ($350.00) for such Month with respect to each such receipt point or delivery point.

Section 9 - Measurement and Metering 9.1 Transporter shall install, maintain and operate electronic measurement facilities at the receipt points and shall measure all Gas received from shipper and other parties. The measurement facilities shall be constructed and installed in accordance with the provisions of the American Gas Association's Gas Measurement Committee Report No. 3 dated September 1985 as amended ("AGA Report"). The volume of Gas shall be computed in accordance with the AGA Report including the appendix thereto. Corrections shall be made for deviation from the Ideal Gas Laws as defined in the AGA Report at the pressure and temperature at which the Gas is metered. To determine the factors for such correction, a qualitative analysis of the Gas shall be made at reasonable intervals but not less than quarterly and such factors shall be obtained from data contained in "Super-compressibility Factors for Natural Gas" Volumes 1 through 6 inclusive, or in "Tables for the Determination of Super-compressibility Factors for Natural Gas Containing Nitrogen and/or Carbon Dioxide", Volume 7, as published by the American Gas Association in 1955 or in subsequent revisions thereof. For the purposes of measurement and meter calibration, the atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be the same atmospheric pressure used by the pipeline at the delivery point without regard to variations in natural atmospheric pressure from time to time. 9.2 The specific gravity of the Gas flowing through a meter at a receipt point shall be determined by Transporter using Gas samples by chromatography or other means commonly used in the Gas industry, at such intervals as may be practicable under the circumstances, but not less than quarterly. The specific gravity of the Gas flowing through a meter shall be used in computing the volume of Gas delivered through such meter. The specific gravity determined by any test shall apply from the first day of the Month in which the test was taken until the date the next test is effective. 9.3 The temperature of the Gas transported under a transportation agreement shall be determined by a recording thermometer at each meter and the arithmetic average of the hourly temperatures recorded each Day shall be used in computing the volumes delivered for that Day. 9.4 The accuracy of Transporter's measuring equipment shall be verified by test, using means and methods generally acceptable in the Gas industry, at least once every ninety (90) Days. Notice of each test shall be given by Transporter to shipper sufficiently in advance to provide shipper with a reasonable opportunity to be present. Measuring equipment found to be registering inaccurately shall be adjusted to read as accurately as possible. If, after notice, shipper fails to have a representative present, the results of the test shall nevertheless be considered accurate until the next test. Transporter shall, upon written request from shipper, conduct a test of Transporter's measuring equipment, provided that in no event shall Transporter be required to test its equipment more frequently than once per Month. All tests of such measuring equipment shall be made at Transporter's expense, except that shipper shall bear the expense of tests made at its request if the inaccuracy is found to be two percent (2%) or less. 9.5 If any measuring equipment is inoperative or inaccurate by more than two percent (2%) in the measurement of Gas, the volume of Gas received, during the period of such inaccuracy shall be determined on the basis of the best data available using the first of the following methods which is feasible: (a) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment installed and accurately registering; (b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculations; or (c) By comparing deliveries made during preceding periods under similar delivery conditions when the meter was registering accurately. An adjustment based on such determination shall be made for such period of inaccuracy as may be definitely known or agreed upon by Transporter and shipper, or if not known, then for one-half the period since the date of the last meter test. 9.6 Each party shall have the right to inspect the other party's equipment, electronic flow measurement data and other measurement or test data during normal business hours, but the reading, calibration and adjustment of such equipment shall be done by the party installing and furnishing same. Unless the parties otherwise agree, each party shall preserve all of its original test data, electronic flow measurement data and other similar records for a period of at least two (2) Years. 9.7 The unit of volume for measurement for all purposes under a transportation agreement shall mean and be measured in terms of one (1) cubic foot of Gas at Standard Base Conditions. The volume of Gas shall be corrected for deviation from Boyle's Law, with correction determined in accordance with accepted Gas industry practices. If Gas contains greater than seven (7) pounds of water vapor per million cubic feet, the Gas shall be deemed, for purposes of this Operating Statement, fully saturated. The Heating Value of and the number of Btu contained in Gas shall mean, and be measured in terms of, the gross number of Btu that would be contained in the volume of such Gas when fully saturated with water vapor and at Standard Base Conditions. If Gas contains less than seven (7) pounds of water vapor per million cubic feet of Gas, then the Heating Value of and the number of Btu contained in Gas shall mean, and be measured in terms of, the gross number of Btu that would be contained in the volume of such Gas when deemed free of water vapor. The Btu contained in hydrogen sulfide or other non-hydrocarbon components will be excluded in any calculation of the number of Btu contained in Gas under a transportation agreement. 9.8 Transporter may install, maintain and operate measurement facilities at the delivery points and measure the Gas so delivered in which event the foregoing provisions of Section 9 shall also be applicable to such measurement facilities; otherwise, the parties shall rely on measurement and test information provided by the pipelines receiving Gas from Transporter at the delivery points for all purposes of measuring Gas delivered at the delivery point, even if the methods employed differ from the foregoing. 9.9 It is recognized that the Gas delivered to the delivery points for shipper's account will be commingled with other Gas, and Gas that Transporter delivers may not be the same Gas received from shipper for transportation under its transportation agreement.

Section 8 - Quality 8.1 The Gas received at each receipt point shall meet the most restrictive quality specifications of any downstream pipeline(s) to which Transporter is delivering Gas for the account of shipper. 8.2 If Gas delivered by shipper to Transporter at a receipt point fails to meet the quality specifications set forth above ("nonconforming Gas"), Transporter may refuse to accept delivery of such Gas until shipper or shipper's supplier has corrected the quality deficiency. Transporter's option to refuse acceptance of nonconforming Gas is in addition to other remedies available to Transporter. If Transporter at any time accepts delivery of nonconforming Gas, such acceptance shall not constitute a waiver of this provision or any other provision of this Operating Statement or the transportation agreement with respect to such Gas accepted or any future delivery of Gas. 8.3 Shipper is obligated to install and operate at its sole expense any compression equipment necessary in order for shipper's Gas to be delivered into the facilities of Transporter. In no event shall Transporter be obligated to install or operate compression or any other facilities in order to provide the transportation services under a transportation agreement.

Section 13 - Indemnification SHIPPER COVENANTS THAT IT SHALL INDEMNIFY AND SAVE TRANSPORTER HARMLESS FROM AND AGAINST ANY AND ALL SUITS, ACTIONS, CAUSES OF ACTIONS, CLAIMS, AND DEMANDS ARISING FROM OR OUT OF ANY ADVERSE CLAIMS OF OWNERSHIP OF OR AN INTEREST IN THE GAS TENDERED FOR TRANSPORTATION HEREUNDER, DAMAGES TO TRANSPORTER'S FACILITIES OR CLAIMS FOR DAMAGES FROM THE QUALITY (OR LACK THEREOF) OF SHIPPER'S GAS, OR CLAIMS FOR DAMAGES FROM SHIPPER'S GAS BEFORE TRANSPORTER'S RECEIPT OF SHIPPER'S GAS OR AFTER DELIVERY OF SHIPPER'S GAS, IRRESPECTIVE OF WHETHER SUCH CLAIMS ARE ATTRIBUTABLE IN WHOLE OR IN PART TO TRANSPORTER'S NEGLIGENCE.

Section 12 - Warranties Shipper warrants (i) it has either title to all Gas delivered by it under the transportation agreement for its account, or that it has the right to deliver Gas; (ii) that such Gas is free from liens and adverse claims of every kind; and (iii) that such Gas is free from defects or impurities that could be injurious to Transporter's system or the health or property of third parties. Shipper shall indemnify and save Transporter harmless against all losses, damages and expenses of every character with respect to the breach of the above warranties or on account of royalties, taxes, payments, or other charges applicable before or upon delivery of Gas under the transportation agreement. Shipper further represents and warrants to Transporter that the transportation of Gas under the transportation agreement shall be on behalf of an interstate pipeline, or on behalf of a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline, as contemplated under Section 311 of the NGPA and the regulations implementing Section 311.

Section 11 - Ownership and Control 11.1 As between Transporter and shipper, shipper shall be in control and in possession of Gas delivered under the transportation agreement and responsible for any damages or injuries caused thereby until Gas is received by Transporter at the receipt points. After receipt of Gas at the receipt points, Transporter shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession thereof and responsible for any injuries or damages caused thereby until the Gas is delivered for the account of shipper at the delivery points, except to the extent such injury or damage is attributable to the failure of shipper's Gas to meet the quality specifications set forth in Section 8; provided, that the parties understand and acknowledge that title to all Gas transported under the transportation agreement at all times remains with shipper. 11.2 Transporter has the right, without liability to shipper, to interrupt the transportation of natural Gas for shipper's account when necessary to test, alter, modify, enlarge, maintain or repair any facility or property comprising part of, or pertinent to, Transporter's transmission system, or otherwise related to the operation thereof. Transporter shall endeavor to cause a minimum amount of inconvenience to shipper. Except in cases of unforeseen emergencies, Transporter shall give shipper advance notice of its intention to curtail the transportation of Gas for shipper's account and of the expected magnitude of such curtailments.

UNITED STATES OF AMERICA BEFORE THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION
OPERATING STATEMENT OF AETHON UNITED PIPELINE LP
Section 1 - Definitions
Except as otherwise herein provided, the following words and/or terms as used in this Operating Statement and any transportation agreement shall have the following scope and meaning:
1.1 The term "Authorized Overrun Quantities" shall mean interruptible quantities nominated by shipper over and above the Demand Quantity that are approved and confirmed by Transporter pursuant to Authorized Overrun Service as described in paragraph 5.3 herein.
1.2 The term "Day" shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time.
1.3 The term "Month" shall mean the period beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first Day of the calendar Month and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first Day of the next succeeding calendar Month.
1.4 The term "Year" shall mean a period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive Days provided, however, that any such Year which contains a date of February 29 shall consist of three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive Days.
1.5 The term "Contract Year" shall mean a one Year period beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the effective date of a transportation agreement.
1.6 The terms "Gas" and "Natural Gas" shall mean natural gas as produced in its natural state whether or not stored or processed prior to delivery, natural gas or any other component thereof that has been previously liquefied and restored to its gaseous state prior to delivery to shipper, gas synthesized or manufactured from oil, naphtha, coal or any other material that meets the quality standards contained in this Operating Statement and which Transporter elects to deliver in lieu of or commingled with one or more of the types of gas described herein.
1.7 The term "Mcf" shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of Gas as determined based on the measurement provisions set forth in Section 9 of this Operating Statement.
1.8 The terms "British thermal unit" or "Btu" shall mean the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of pure water from fifty-eight and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (58.5?F) to fifty-nine and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (59.5?F).
1.9 The term "MMBtu" shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu.
1.10 The term "Heating Value" shall mean the gross number of Btu determined on a dry basis, produced by the combustion at constant pressure of the amount of Gas which would occupy a volume of one (1) cubic foot at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60?F), under a pressure equivalent to that of thirty (30) inches of mercury at thirty-two degrees Fahrenheit (32?F) and under gravitational force (acceleration 980.665 cm. per sec. per sec.) with air of the same temperature and pressure as the Gas, when the products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the Gas and air, and when the water formed by combustion is condensed to the liquid state, and expressed at a pressure base of fifteen and twenty-five thousandths (15.025) pounds per square inch absolute ("psia"). Where a chromatograph is used instead of a calorimeter, the gross Btu shall be determined by analysis but shall be on the equivalent basis as above.
1.11 The terms "Point(s) of Receipt" or "receipt points" shall mean those points identified as such in a transportation agreement.
1.12 The terms "Point(s) of Delivery" or "delivery points" shall mean those points identified as such in a transportation agreement.
1.13 The term "Standard Base Conditions" shall mean fifteen and twenty-five thousandths (15.025) psia and sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60?F).
1.14 The term "Fuel" shall mean Transporter's compressor fuel, equivalents (including electricity or other energy sources) and use requirements, and Gas lost or unaccounted for on its system, as well as any incremental compressor fuel incurred by Transporter to compress the Gas in order to receive the Gas at the receipt points or deliver the Gas at the delivery points.

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 16 - Waiver Transporter may waive a shipper's violation of the terms and conditions set forth in this Operating Statement, without undue discrimination or preference and without consent from any shipper, when in Transporter's reasonable judgment such action is necessary or appropriate or consistent with reasonable business practices, and Transporter shall be without liability to any shipper for such action.

Section 6 - Priority of Service 6.1 If Transporter determines that the total quantity of Gas at any point on or through any portion of Transporter's pipeline system exceeds the capacity of such point or portion of Transporter's pipeline system, Transporter shall schedule or curtail Gas based on the following criteria: (a) Firm transportation shall have the highest priority for nomination, scheduling and curtailment. If full service cannot be provided to all firm shippers, then Transporter shall curtail all firm shippers on a proportional basis. (b) Interruptible transportation service shall be scheduled when, and to the extent that, in Transporter's sole opinion, capacity is available on its pipeline system after first scheduling all firm transportation service and considering pipeline operational requirements. Among interruptible shippers, those shippers paying the highest rate shall be given priority for transportation service, giving priority from highest rate to lowest rate. If two or more shippers are entitled to the same priority, then priority among them shall be given to the shipper having the earlier contract date. (c) Authorized overrun service shall be scheduled when, and to the extent that, in Transporter's sole opinion, capacity is available on its pipeline system after first scheduling all firm and interruptible transportation service and considering pipeline operational requirements. Among authorized overrun service shippers, those shippers paying the highest rate shall be given priority for transportation service, giving priority from highest rate to lowest rate. If two or more shippers are entitled to the same priority, then priority among them shall be given to the shipper having the earlier contract date. 6.2 Available capacity at any receipt point, delivery point, or any other point on or through Transporter's pipeline system shall be based on Transporter's sole evaluation of operational conditions on its pipeline system, including, but not limited to, pipeline pressures, compressors, interconnected pipeline pressures, limitations and capabilities, and other operational conditions as they may exist from time to time. Available capacity may be limited at Transporter's discretion.

Section 2 - Introduction Aethon United Pipeline LP ("Transporter"), a Delaware corporation and intrastate pipeline, currently engages in the transportation of Natural Gas for third parties through pipeline facilities in Louisiana under Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 ("NGPA") as amended and the applicable rules and regulations promulgated thereunder by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC"). These pipeline facilities are jointly owned by Aethon United Pipeline LP and PEO Haynesville Pipeline LLC, on whose behalf Transporter operates the pipeline facilities. Currently, Transporter offers transportation service pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA on its Gravel Point South Line. This Operating Statement describes the administrative and operational policies and procedures of Transporter regarding transportation services conducted under Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA for any eligible shipper. Transporter shall be satisfied of shipper's solvency, based on reasonable standards of creditworthiness that shall be applied on a nondiscriminatory basis. It is the policy of Transporter to render such transportation services under written transportation agreements containing the terms and conditions generally acceptable to Transporter and in accordance with those additional terms and conditions set forth herein, executed after consideration of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, receipt points and delivery points, and other factors deemed material by Transporter. Transporter reserves the right to vary from such general terms when business or operational conditions dictate, provided that any such variations are not materially detrimental to any other shipper similarly situated. If conflicts arise between the provisions of this Operating Statement and a transportation agreement, the provisions of this Operating Statement shall govern.

STATEMENT OF RATES Transporter's maximum rates for transportation services pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA are based on the methodology set forth in 18 CFR Section 284.124(b)(2) and were approved by FERC. Transporter's maximum rates, effective December 1, 2018, are as follows: Firm Transportation Services: daily reservation fee $0.0152 per MMBtu per Day commodity fee $0.00 per MMBtu Interruptible Transportation Services: transportation fee $0.0152 per MMBtu Authorized Overrun Service transportation fee $0.0152 per MMBtu Metering Fee: $350 per Month (if applicable per Section 10) Fuel Retention actual quantity of Fuel, in MMBtu, allocated on a proportional basis to shipper, not to exceed 2.0% of Gas received by Transporter

Section 21 - Creditworthiness 21.1 Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper (i) that has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) that fails to make prompt and full payment to Transporter when due for services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) for which Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity as to Shipper's performance of its obligations under any transaction governed hereby. If any event set forth in (i), (ii) or (iii) shall occur, in addition to any other rights or remedies available to Transporter, it may in writing demand adequate assurance of due performance and until it receives such assurance, may suspend any performance for which it has not already been paid. 21.2 Adequate assurance of performance of the type described in Paragraph 22.1 above shall include (i) posting of a letter of credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; (ii) cash prepayment in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; or (iii) delivery of other forms of security acceptable to the Transporter in an amount equal to three months of demand charges. Shipper's failure to deliver adequate assurance properly demanded within two business days of receiving Transporter's demand therefore shall constitute a breach of the applicable transportation transaction, entitling Transporter to (i) terminate any or all transportation transactions with Shipper, (ii) liquidate Gas balances in Transporter's possession and applying the resulting funds to the payment of all amounts owed and that become owed for services under any transportation transactions governed by this statement of operating conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach for all applicable transportation transactions.
